  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. Generally, a conviction can result in:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering\n\n2. Financial Penalties:\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or double the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Civil asset forfeiture\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances like transaction amount, criminal history, and whether the case involves international or domestic money laundering. Specific statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act govern these prosecutions.\n\nExact sentencing can vary based on individual case details, so consulting a legal professional would provide the most accurate assessment for a specific situation.",
